  "why": "The paper explicitly identifies input fidelity, defined as \"preserving original semantics and looking natural to humans,\" as a critical criterion. To enforce this, the proposed method, DRFuzz, incorporates a \"GAN-based Fidelity Assurance\" component. A discriminator, trained on the original dataset, learns the distribution of plausible inputs. During the fuzzing process, every mutated input is evaluated by this discriminator to filter out low-fidelity samples. This approach directly restricts the search to a learned plausible distribution, which is a key characteristic of the 'High' rating. By checking each mutant against this global model of plausibility, the method effectively prevents cumulative distortion across multiple mutation iterations, rather than just controlling the change between successive steps. The paper's ablation study empirically validates this, showing the GAN component filters out over 20% of low-fidelity inputs that would otherwise be considered, and manual inspection confirms that 86% of the final inputs are high-fidelity.",
